You have built a sophisticated intelligence engine riding on a fragile scaffold. The AI logic — 3-pass compiler, LangGraph specialists, deterministic SQL/PySpark codegen templates — is genuinely impressive. The surrounding structure — job durability, auth model, error contracts, state synchronization, test isolation — is prototype-grade. That gap is the source of every debugging session that took 3+ days.

1. INGESTION (SQL / Blob / Local) — Structural pass; two confirmed bombs
What works: Three paths feeding one unified assessment_orchestrator.py is the right design.

Boot-time bomb confirmed in pyspark_codegen.py line 7:

python

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession  # ← hard module-level import
This crashes your entire FastAPI server on startup in any environment without PySpark (local dev, CI, Docker without Spark). It's not a smell — it's an active crash.

Fix (10 minutes): Move all PySpark imports inside the functions that call them:

python

def _emit_fill_spark(...):
    from pyspark.sql import functions as F  # lazy import
Blob-specific gap confirmed: No format_readers.py or deterministic per-format dispatcher exists anywhere. PySpark file reading (CSV vs JSON vs Parquet vs XML) is LLM-driven — this is why blob ETL execution fails inconsistently by file type. The LLM shouldn't decide spark.read syntax. That's a deterministic fact.

Fix (1 day): Build format_readers.py:

python

def read_csv(path): return spark.read.option("header","true").option("inferSchema","true").csv(path)
def read_json(path): return spark.read.json(path)
def read_parquet(path): return spark.read.parquet(path)
def read_xml(path, row_tag): return spark.read.format("xml").option("rowTag", row_tag).load(path)
Codegen selects based on detected format metadata — LLM only writes the cleaning logic.

